const faqSchema = { '@context': 'https://schema.org', '@type': 'FAQPage', mainEntity: [
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What does turkey tail mushroom do for the immune system?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Turkey tail (Trametes versicolor) contains two primary bioactive polysaccharides: PSK (polysaccharopeptide Krestin) and PSP (polysaccharopeptide). These compounds are potent immunomodulators that activate multiple immune cell types: natural killer cells (innate defense against viruses and cancer cells), T-cells (adaptive immune targeting), macrophages (pathogen engulfment and antigen presentation), and dendritic cells (immune system education). PSK has been approved as an adjunct cancer therapy in Japan since the 1970s and is covered by Japanese national health insurance. Over 400 published studies support turkey tail\'s immune-modulating properties, making it the most clinically researched medicinal mushroom for immune function.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What is the difference between fruiting body and mycelium turkey tail?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The fruiting body is the visible mushroom cap — the colorful fan-shaped structure that grows on dead trees. It contains the highest concentrations of beta-glucans, PSK, and PSP — the bioactive compounds responsible for immune benefits. Mycelium is the root-like network that grows through a substrate (usually grain). Mycelium-based products often contain significant amounts of the grain substrate (starch), which dilutes the mushroom compound concentration. Independent testing has shown some mycelium-on-grain products contain as little as 5% actual mushroom compounds, with the rest being grain starch. Fruiting body extracts consistently contain higher beta-glucan levels (30-50%) compared to mycelium-on-grain products (5-15%).' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How much turkey tail should I take daily?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Clinical studies on turkey tail have used a wide dose range: 1-3g per day for general immune support, and up to 9g per day in oncology research (PSK adjunct therapy). For daily immune maintenance, 1-2g of turkey tail extract per day is the most commonly recommended dose. Most turkey tail gummies provide 500mg-1g per serving, so 1-2 servings daily covers the maintenance range. Look for products that disclose beta-glucan content — a minimum of 30% beta-glucans indicates a quality extract. Higher beta-glucan percentages (40-50%) indicate more concentrated immune-active compounds per milligram.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Can turkey tail mushroom help with cancer?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Turkey tail\'s PSK (Krestin) has been used as an adjunct cancer therapy in Japan since the 1970s, prescribed alongside conventional chemotherapy for gastric, colorectal, and lung cancers. A meta-analysis of over 8,000 patients found that PSK combined with chemotherapy improved 5-year survival rates compared to chemotherapy alone. In the US, an NIH-funded Phase I clinical trial at the University of Washington found that turkey tail improved immune function in breast cancer patients after radiation therapy. However, turkey tail is NOT a replacement for conventional cancer treatment — it is a complementary immune support used alongside medical oncology. Always discuss mushroom supplements with your oncologist.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Is turkey tail good for gut health?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes. Turkey tail is one of the best natural prebiotics available. Its polysaccharides — particularly beta-glucans and other complex carbohydrates — are not digested in the upper GI tract but are fermented by beneficial gut bacteria in the colon. This fermentation produces short-chain fatty acids (SCFAs) including butyrate, which nourishes intestinal epithelial cells, reduces gut inflammation, and strengthens the gut barrier. A 2014 study found that turkey tail PSP increased populations of Bifidobacterium and Lactobacillus (beneficial bacteria) while reducing populations of potentially harmful Clostridium and Staphylococcus species.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Are turkey tail gummies safe?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Turkey tail mushroom is considered very safe with a long history of human consumption and clinical use. In Japan, PSK has been prescribed to millions of patients since the 1970s with minimal reported side effects. The most common side effects are mild digestive symptoms (gas, bloating) in some individuals, particularly when starting supplementation. People with mushroom allergies should avoid turkey tail. Those with autoimmune conditions should consult their physician, as immune-stimulating mushrooms may theoretically activate autoimmune responses. Cancer patients should discuss turkey tail with their oncologist before use, as it may interact with immunotherapy treatments.' } },
] };
