    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Turkey Tail Gummies</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What does turkey tail do for the immune system?</summary><p>Turkey tail contains PSK and PSP — immunomodulators that activate NK cells, T-cells, macrophages, and dendritic cells. PSK has been used as adjunct cancer therapy in Japan since the 1970s. Over 400 published studies document turkey tail's immune properties.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Fruiting body vs mycelium — what is the difference?</summary><p>Fruiting body (visible mushroom) contains 30-50% beta-glucans. Mycelium-on-grain products contain 5-15% beta-glucans diluted by grain starch. This difference determines immune supplement effectiveness. Look for "100% fruiting body" and verified beta-glucan content.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much turkey tail should I take daily?</summary><p>General immune support: 1-2g extract daily. Oncology adjunct: up to 9g daily (clinical doses). Most gummies provide 500mg-1g per serving. Look for 30%+ beta-glucans for quality confirmation.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can turkey tail help with cancer?</summary><p>PSK has improved 5-year survival rates in Japanese clinical trials when combined with chemotherapy. An NIH trial confirmed immune benefits for breast cancer patients. Turkey tail is complementary to (NOT a replacement for) conventional cancer treatment. Always consult your oncologist.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Is turkey tail good for gut health?</summary><p>Yes. Turkey tail polysaccharides are potent prebiotics fermented by beneficial gut bacteria, producing butyrate. Studies show increased Bifidobacterium and Lactobacillus populations. Gut health directly supports immune function.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Are turkey tail gummies safe?</summary><p>Very safe with decades of pharmaceutical use in Japan. Mild GI symptoms possible when starting. Avoid with mushroom allergies. Consult physician for autoimmune conditions. Cancer patients should coordinate with their oncologist.</p></details>

